Title: The Art of Connection: Engaging Teens on Their Terms - Interview w Ben Pugh
Description: Welcome to the labyrinth of adolescence, where every step/parent feels like they need a map, a guide, and maybe a little magic to navigate. If you‚Äôve ever felt like you're speaking a different language than your teen, you‚Äôre not alone. This episode is your Rosetta Stone to understanding and connecting with the enigmatic creatures known as teenagers. In Today‚Äôs Episode: "The Art of Connection: Engaging Teens on Their Terms" We‚Äôre diving headfirst into the teenage brain with the sage guidance of Ben Pugh, a veritable Gandalf in the world of parenting and teen communication. With a resume that reads like a heroic saga - from foster parenting and high school principal to a beloved football coach turned life coach - Ben brings a treasure trove of insights to the table. Why This Episode Is Like Finding Parenting Gold: Teen Speak Decoded : Ever wish you had a decoder ring for teen grunts, eye rolls, and the infamous "fine"? Ben's here to translate. Change Your Lens, Not Your Teen : Discover the transformational power of shifting your perspective, not your teen‚Äôs personality. Peace Talks Over Power Struggles : Learn how to turn confrontations into conversations that actually lead somewhere (other than slamming doors). Navigating the Digital Divide : Yes, there's a way to talk to your teen that doesn't involve banning TikTok. Ben Pugh: The Parent Whisperer In a world where "because I said so" meets eye-rolling indifference, Ben stands as a beacon of hope and humor. Through his acclaimed IMPACT program and podcast, "IMPACT: Parenting with Perspective," Ben is revolutionizing how we connect with our teens. His approach? Understanding, not ultimatums; connection, not correction. Episode Highlights You Can‚Äôt Afford to Miss: Tales from the Trenches: Real stories of breakthroughs and belly laughs in the quest to connect with teens. Why Laughter Might Be Your Best Parenting Tool: Ben shares how humor can bridge the widest of generation gaps. Fresh, Actionable Strategies: Forget outdated advice. Get ready for innovative ways to engage with your teen that resonate with their world today. Before You Go: Connecting with your teen on their terms doesn‚Äôt mean losing your parental identity. It‚Äôs about enriching it with understanding, empathy, and, yes, a good dose of shared laughter. So plug in, turn up the volume, and get ready to see your teen in a whole new light with Ben Pugh. P.S. Loved the journey into the heart of teen communication? Title: 170: Three Myths About What Your Days Will Look Like After You Finish Homeschooling
Description: Have you thought about what your days will look like when you finish homeschooling? As my daughter was progressing through high school, I started thinking about what the empty nest years might look like. I'll be honest and say that I'm looking forward to them! It's no secret around here. I will miss my daughters' daily presence, but there is also a lot I'm looking forward to about them both graduating and moving out. It will mean more independence and freedom for all of us. We have graduated one daughter; the other is in high school. We are not fully empty nesting yet, but we have changed our family dynamics from a family of four to having an only child for most of the week, and she is a busy little bee with activities and friends. As we moved into this stage, I had thoughts about what the days would look like and how things would be. I was wrong about several of them.
